e 0. $$ Then there exists some neighborhood $U(x^0) \subseteq \mathbb R^n$ and a function $f : U(x^0) 	o \mathbb R$ such that  $$  y = f(x_1, \ldots, x_n), \qquad  y_0 = f(x_1^0, \ldots, x_n^0) $$ and $$  F(x, f(x)) = 0 $$ and $f \in C^1(U(x^0))$. Now the Implicit Function Theorem reads as Theorem 2 (Implicit Function Theorem): Let $F : G \subseteq \mathbb R^{n+m} 	o \mathbb R^m$, $G
e \emptyset$, $F \in C^1(G)$, $G$ open. Also $(x^0, y^0) \in G$ with $x^0 \in \mathbb R^n, y^0 \in \mathbb R^m, F(x^0,y^0) = 0$ and $$  \det\left(  rac{\partial F}{\partial y} ight)_{y=y_0} 
e 0. $$ Then there exists neighborhoods $U(x^0) \subseteq \mathbb R^n, V(y^0) \subseteq \mathbb R^m$ and a function $g : U(x^0) 	o V(x^0)$ such that $F(x, g(x)) = 0$ on $x \in U(x^0)$. Proof: The proof proceeds by induction on $m$, if $m = 1$ it is Theorem 1, so we assume $m > 1$ and suppose (by induction hypothesis) the statement holds for $m-1$. Let $F : G \subseteq \mathbb R^{n+m} 	o \mathbb R^n$ be given, then because of $$  \det\left(  rac{\partial F}{\partial y} ight)_{y=y_0} 
e 0  \quad \mbox{ or } \quad \det  egin{pmatrix}    rac{\partial F_1}{\partial y_1} &  rac{\partial F_1}{\partial y_2} & \cdots &  rac{\partial F_1}{\partial y_m} \   \vdots \    rac{\partial F_m}{\partial y_1} &  rac{\partial F_m}{\partial y_2} & \cdots &  rac{\partial F_m}{\partial y_m}   \end{pmatrix} 
e 0. $$ So we can suppose that every row contains an entry $
e 0$, suppose w.l.o.g. that  $ rac{\partial F_m}{\partial y_m} 
e 0$. By Theorem 1 we can solve (locally) for $y_m$, that means there is some neighborhood $U$ of $(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1})$ and a function $$  y_m = \varphi(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1}) $$ and $\varphi$ is continously differentiable with ($x \in \mathbb R^n$) $$  F_m(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1}, \varphi(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1})) = 0 $$ for all $(x,y_1,\ldots,y_{m-1}) \in U$. Now set  $$  \Phi_i(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1}) := F_i(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1}, \varphi(x, y_1, \ldots, y_{m-1})) $$ for $i = 1, \ldots, m-1$. Then $\Phi : U \subseteq \mathbb R^{n+m-1} 	o \mathbb R^{m-1}$ and $\Phi$ fulfills als prerequisites to apply the induction hypothesis (here the proof shows this, but I omit it because it is quite long and does not apply to my question). Then there exists neighborhoods $W \subseteq \mathbb R^n, V \subseteq \mathbb R^{m-1}$ and a function $g : W 	o V$ with $$  \Phi(x, g(x)) = 0 $$ for all $x \in W$. Now set $h(x) = (g(x), \varphi(x,g(x))$, then we have $$  F(x, h(x)) = 0 $$ and the proof is finished. $\square$ My question is on the last part. Namely the construction of the function $h(x)$, 1) Because $h(x) = (g(x), \varphi(x, g(x))$ it must be the case that $(x, g(x) \in U$, because $\varphi : U 	o \mathbb R$, but I do not see that this must be the case? 2) The same issue if I want to show that $F(x, h(x)) = 0$, if $i 
e m$ it is $$  F_i(x, h(x)) = \Phi_i(x, g(x)) $$ by definition, but for $$  F_m(x, h(x)) = F_m(x, g(x), \varphi(x,g(x)) = F_m(x, g_1(x), \ldots, g_{m-1}(x), \varphi(x, g_1(x), \ldots, g_{m-1}(x)) $$ and to conclude that this equals $0$ it also must be that $(x, g(x)) \in U$, but I do not see that this must be the case?

